				\begin{document}$$F = \frac{{24 \cdot {\text{HLC}} \cdot \left( {\text{HDD}} \right)}}{\eta } + B,$$\end{document}where F is the fuel consumption for the period (kWh), η is the overall heating system efficiency for that period, HLC is the overall building heat loss coefficient (kW/K), which includes the heat conduction losses, the air infiltration and the ventilation losses, and B is a constant value that corresponds to other possible non-weather dependant gas consumptions. The degree-days for the period, HDD, are found as the sum of the daily degree days, Dd, over the considered billing period (about a month) using the most rigorous method, with exterior hourly temperature data. The daily degree days can be expressed according to (Eq. 2):2Dd=∑124Thb-Text,iThb-Text,i>024,\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
